{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"0655fa36477bada3e2497c5d078df346","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\n\n(I answered this earlier in this conversation — here's the summary.)\n\n**1. Per-fact revalidation instead of all-or-nothing**\n\nCurrently if `verifyFactsheetStatic` throws, the entire factsheet is marked stale. Catch per-fact failures and only reject individual facts, keeping those still verifiable. Already tracked by `rejected_facts` in the output — just wire it up granularly in `refreshCluster` instead of failing the whole factsheet.\n\n**2. Distinguish file-hash-changed from selector-actually-changed**\n\n`findChangedFiles` flags any file whose hash differs. But a changed hash doesn't prove the cited `selector` text moved. Add a per-selector recheck: for changed files, re-read and verify each `selector` string + `snippet_hash`. Only mark stale if the selector actually changed. This avoids false stale-marks when a file has unrelated edits.\n\n**3. Schedule LLM re-verification after N days even on clean static pass**\n\nAn `llm_verified` factsheet can go stale semantically even when all static evidence still checks out (e.g. code was refactored in a way that invalidates a claim but not the exact selector text). Track `refresh_age_days` and if it exceeds a config threshold for an `llm_verified` factsheet, log an `llm_reverify_scheduled` event and mark it `needs_prepare` rather than `active/fresh`. The existing trust-state semantics are unchanged; this only pre-empts future consults from trusting an aged factsheet."}],"model":"MiniMax-M2.7","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":113279,"output_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0},"service_tier":"standard","context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b299724c-1497-410c-96dd-2f782477c674","uuid":"47f41d46-8cc8-4b05-80c4-83b0b9a2c31d"}
{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":8406,"duration_api_ms":8374,"num_turns":1,"result":"\n\n(I answered this earlier in this conversation — here's the summary.)\n\n**1. Per-fact revalidation instead of all-or-nothing**\n\nCurrently if `verifyFactsheetStatic` throws, the entire factsheet is marked stale. Catch per-fact failures and only reject individual facts, keeping those still verifiable. Already tracked by `rejected_facts` in the output — just wire it up granularly in `refreshCluster` instead of failing the whole factsheet.\n\n**2. Distinguish file-hash-changed from selector-actually-changed**\n\n`findChangedFiles` flags any file whose hash differs. But a changed hash doesn't prove the cited `selector` text moved. Add a per-selector recheck: for changed files, re-read and verify each `selector` string + `snippet_hash`. Only mark stale if the selector actually changed. This avoids false stale-marks when a file has unrelated edits.\n\n**3. Schedule LLM re-verification after N days even on clean static pass**\n\nAn `llm_verified` factsheet can go stale semantically even when all static evidence still checks out (e.g. code was refactored in a way that invalidates a claim but not the exact selector text). Track `refresh_age_days` and if it exceeds a config threshold for an `llm_verified` factsheet, log an `llm_reverify_scheduled` event and mark it `needs_prepare` rather than `active/fresh`. The existing trust-state semantics are unchanged; this only pre-empts future consults from trusting an aged factsheet.","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"b299724c-1497-410c-96dd-2f782477c674","total_cost_usd":0.079617,"usage":{"input_tokens":2863,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":112704,"output_tokens":358,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"st